.IX Title "HTML::Format 3"
.TH HTML::Format 3 "2008-03-09" "perl v5.8.6" "User Contributed Perl Documentation"
.SH "NAME"
HTML::Format \- Format Perl data structures into simple HTML
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\& use HTML::Format;
.Ve
.PP
.Vb 1
\& my $f = HTML::Format->new;
.Ve
.PP
.Vb 1
\& my %hash = (simple => 'hash');
.Ve
.PP
.Vb 15
\& # Of course it's very unlikely that you won't deal ever with this
\& # kind of structure, but HTML is able to hand it all anyway :)
\& my $struct = {
\&        foo                             => 'bar',
\&        1                                       => 2,
\&        \e'hello'                        => 'goodbye',
\&        array_ref                       => [qw/one two three/],
\&        nested_hash                     => \e%hash,
\&        [qw/1 2/]                       => sub { die; },
\&        even_more                       => { arr => {
\&                        1 => [2, 3, 4],
\&                        this_is_insane => { a => { b => { c => { d => { e => 'z'}}}}}
\&                },                                      
\&        },
\& };
.Ve
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $struct->{'HTML::Format handles it all'} = $f;
.Ve
.PP
.Vb 1
\& print $f->format();
.Ve
.PP
And that will output the following insane, but possible, for the sake
of showing, \s-1HTML:\s0
.PP
In theory you can pass any kind of Perl data structure to \f(CW\*(C`format\*(C'\fR
and you will get its data HTML\-formatted.
